Part I: Rigorous Foundations

Chapter 2: Preliminaries

2.1 Zermelo‑Fraenkel Set Theory with the Anti‑Foundation Axiom

We work in ZFC (Zermelo‑Fraenkel with Choice) augmented with Aczel’s Anti‑Foundation Axiom (AFA). AFA allows the construction of non‑well‑founded sets (hypersets) that can contain themselves. The key concept is that of an accessible pointed graph (apg): a directed graph with a distinguished node such that every node is reachable from the distinguished node.

Definition 2.1 (Aczel 1988). An accessible pointed graph is a triple (G, \to, r) where G is a set of vertices, \to \subseteq G \times G is the edge relation, and r \in G is a root, with the property that every node is reachable from r via a finite directed path.

Definition 2.2 (Decoration). A decoration of an apg (G,\to,r) is a function d: G \to V (where V is the universe of sets) such that for every x \in G,

d(x) = \{ d(y) : x \to y \}.

Axiom 2.3 (AFA). Every apg has a unique decoration.

A consequence of AFA is that the equation x = \{x\} (the Quine atom) has a unique solution; more generally, systems of set equations have unique solutions.

2.2 Coalgebras and Final Coalgebras

Let \mathbf{Set} denote the category of sets and functions. For an endofunctor F : \mathbf{Set} \to \mathbf{Set}, an F-coalgebra is a pair (X, \alpha) with \alpha : X \to F(X). A homomorphism from (X,\alpha) to (Y,\beta) is a function f : X \to Y such that \beta \circ f = F(f) \circ \alpha. A final coalgebra is a terminal object in the category of F-coalgebras; it exists for many functors (e.g., polynomial functors) and can be constructed as the limit of the final chain:

1 \xleftarrow{!} F(1) \xleftarrow{F(!)} F^2(1) \xleftarrow{F^2(!)} \cdots

where 1 is a terminal object (a one‑element set). However, for some functors (including \mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{fin}}), the limit of the \omega-chain does not give the final coalgebra; a transfinite iteration of length \omega + \omega is needed (Worrell 1995). In this thesis we avoid this subtlety by working directly with the explicit description of the final coalgebra as the set of all finitely branching trees, as detailed in Chapter 4.

2.3 Kolmogorov Complexity and Logical Depth

To make algorithmic information concepts precise, we fix a universal prefix‑free Turing machine M. For a finite binary string x, define the Kolmogorov complexity K(x) = \min\{ |p| : M(p) = x\}. The universal distribution is m(x) = 2^{-K(x)} (Li & Vitányi 2019).

Logical depth (Bennett 1988) measures the computational time required by the shortest program to produce x. A string can have low Kolmogorov complexity but high logical depth if the shortest program takes a long time to run.

To apply these concepts to sets, we fix a Gödel numbering that encodes finite accessible pointed graphs (or finite trees) as binary strings. All statements about K and logical depth are then understood relative to this fixed encoding.

