Chapter 3: The Minimal Self‑Distinguishing Structure

3.1 Definition and Basic Properties

We define the distinction operator D on the class of sets by

D(X) = \{ X, \emptyset \}.

A set S is called self‑distinguishing if S = D(S), i.e.,

S = \{ S, \emptyset \}. \tag{3.1}

Lemma 3.1 (Existence). Equation (3.1) has a solution in ZFC+AFA.

Proof. Consider the apg G with vertices \{a,b\}, edges a \to a and a \to b, and root a. By AFA, there is a unique decoration d with d(a) = \{ d(a), d(b) \} and d(b) = \emptyset. Thus S_0 := d(a) satisfies (3.1). ∎

Lemma 3.2 (Minimality). Up to bisimulation, there is exactly one solution of (3.1) with the smallest number of vertices in its membership graph; it is the decoration of the two‑vertex apg described above.

Proof. Any solution S must have S \ni S and S \ni \emptyset. Hence its membership graph has at least two vertices (one for S and one for \emptyset) and a self‑loop. The graph with exactly two vertices and a self‑loop is minimal. By the uniqueness of decorations for a given apg, any other solution would have an apg bisimilar to this one, and by the decoration theorem the decorations are equal. Hence the solution is unique up to bisimulation. ∎

We denote this minimal solution by S_0 and call it the primordial distinction.

3.2 Classification of Fixed Points of the Distinction Operator

We can generalize: consider equations of the form S = \{ S, X \} where X is a set. Under AFA, the unique solution for a given X is obtained by decorating the graph with two nodes a and b, edges a\to a and a\to b, and b a childless node decorated by X. The minimal solution (in terms of graph size) is when X = \emptyset. This suggests a classification: the fixed points of the operator D_X(Y) = \{Y,X\} are uniquely determined up to bisimulation by the “background” set X. For X = \emptyset we obtain S_0; for other X we get different hypersets. This observation can be extended to a general theorem about the uniqueness of solutions to such set equations, which is a standard application of AFA.

Theorem 3.3 (Classification). For any set X, there exists a unique (up to bisimulation) hyperset S_X satisfying S_X = \{ S_X, X \}. It is obtained by decorating the two‑vertex apg with root a, edges a\to a and a\to b, and decorating b with X. Moreover, S_X is minimal in the sense that its membership graph has exactly two nodes if and only if X is not itself a member of a smaller graph.

Proof. Immediate from the decoration theorem. ∎

3.3 The Quine Atom Hierarchy (Σₙ)

We now introduce a sequence of hypersets that provide a “backbone” of increasing self‑reference, forming a natural hierarchy within the final coalgebra.

Definition 3.4 (Quine hierarchy). Define \Sigma_0 = \emptyset. For each n \in \mathbb{N}, let \Sigma_{n+1} be the unique solution (given by Theorem 3.3) of the equation

\Sigma_{n+1} = \{ \Sigma_{n+1}, \Sigma_n \}.

Thus \Sigma_1 = S_0, \Sigma_2 satisfies \Sigma_2 = \{\Sigma_2, \Sigma_1\}, and so on.

Lemma 3.5 (Existence and uniqueness). Each \Sigma_n exists and is unique in ZFC+AFA.

Proof. By induction. \Sigma_0 = \emptyset exists. Assuming \Sigma_n exists, the apg with vertices \{a,b\}, edges a\to a and a\to b, and decorating b with \Sigma_n yields a unique decoration \Sigma_{n+1} = d(a). Uniqueness follows from AFA. ∎

Proposition 3.6 (Hierarchy). For each n, \Sigma_n is an element of the final coalgebra U (defined in Chapter 4). Moreover, the membership relation gives \Sigma_{n+1} \in \Sigma_{n+1} and \Sigma_n \in \Sigma_{n+1}, and the transitive closure of \{\Sigma_n\} consists exactly of \{\Sigma_0, \Sigma_1, \dots, \Sigma_n\}.

Proof. The tree representation of \Sigma_n is a finite tree of depth n where each node has exactly two children, with the left child a copy of the whole tree (a self‑loop) and the right child the tree representing \Sigma_{n-1} (or a leaf for \Sigma_0). This is a finitely branching tree, hence belongs to U. The membership claims follow directly from the defining equations. ∎

Thus the \Sigma_n form a countable chain of increasingly complex self‑referential structures, each building on the previous one. They serve as a “coordinate system” within the otherwise chaotic universe U.

