Chapter 4: The Universe as Final Coalgebra

4.1 The Distinction Functor

Define the functor F: \mathbf{Set} \to \mathbf{Set} by

F(X) = \mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{fin}}(X) + 1,

where \mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{fin}}(X) is the set of finite subsets of X, and +1 adds a distinguished element \ast (representing the empty distinction). For a function f: X \to Y, F(f) sends a finite subset A \subseteq X to f[A] \subseteq Y and sends \ast to \ast.

Lemma 4.1. F is a polynomial functor and therefore has a final coalgebra.

Proof. Polynomial functors are those built from constants, products, coproducts, and exponentiation by finite sets. \mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{fin}}(X) can be expressed as \coprod_{n \ge 0} X^n / S_n (symmetric product), which is a polynomial construction. Final coalgebras exist for such functors (Rutten 2000). ∎

4.2 Construction of the Final Coalgebra

We construct the final coalgebra explicitly as the set of all finite and infinite finitely branching trees. A finitely branching tree is a rooted tree in which each node has a finite (possibly zero) set of children. Leaves are labelled by the distinguished symbol \ast. (Infinite branches are allowed, but each node has only finitely many children.)

Let U be the set of all such trees. Define \alpha: U \to F(U) as follows:

· If t is a leaf (i.e., a tree consisting of a single node labelled \ast), set \alpha(t) = \ast (the distinguished element).
· Otherwise, let t have root r with finite set of children C = \{t_1, \dots, t_k\}, where each t_i is the subtree rooted at the i-th child. Then define \alpha(t) = \{t_1, \dots, t_k\} \in \mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{fin}}(U).

Proposition 4.2 (Characterization). The pair (U, \alpha) is a final F-coalgebra. Its elements correspond bijectively to (possibly infinite) finitely branching rooted trees, and the finite‑depth trees correspond exactly to the hereditarily finite hypersets (sets whose transitive closure is finite, possibly containing cycles) via the AFA decoration theorem.

Proof. We first show that every element of U is the unique decoration of its underlying tree considered as an apg. For a tree t, define an apg whose nodes are the nodes of t, edges from parent to children, and root the root of t. This apg is accessible and has a unique decoration by AFA, giving a set. Conversely, any set built from the empty set and the membership relation can be unfolded into a (possibly cyclic) graph; by taking the tree unfolding (which may be infinite if there are cycles), we obtain a finitely branching tree. The correspondence is bijective because two sets are equal iff their tree unfoldings are isomorphic (by the extensionality property of AFA). Finally, (U,\alpha) is final: for any F-coalgebra (X,\beta), define a map h: X \to U by coinduction: for each x \in X, the image is the tree whose root has children \{ h(y) : y \in \beta(x) \} when \beta(x) is a finite set, and is a leaf when \beta(x) = \ast. This map is the unique coalgebra homomorphism. ∎

The finite approximations U_n are defined as the subsets of U consisting of trees of depth at most n (with the root at depth 0). They satisfy U_0 = \{\ast\} and U_{n+1} = F(U_n) as sets, because a tree of depth \le n+1 is either a leaf (depth 0) or a finite set of subtrees each of depth \le n. Hence the cardinality recurrence given in Chapter 5 follows.

We denote the final coalgebra by (U,\alpha) and call it the universe of all consistent distinctions.

4.3 The Subcoalgebra Generated by S_0

The set S_0 is an element of U because its membership graph is a two‑node tree: the root has two children, one of which is a self‑loop (represented by a subtree isomorphic to S_0 itself) and the other is the leaf \emptyset. (Formally, S_0 corresponds to the infinite tree where the root has two children: the left child is a copy of the whole tree, the right child is a leaf.)

Define the subcoalgebra generated by S_0 as the smallest sub‑F-coalgebra of U containing S_0. Concretely, let U' \subseteq U be the set of all elements that appear in the transitive closure (under the membership relation) of \{S_0\}.

Proposition 4.3. The subcoalgebra generated by S_0 is exactly \{S_0, \emptyset\}, where \emptyset is the element of U corresponding to the tree consisting of a single leaf labelled \ast. This subcoalgebra has the coalgebra structure:

\alpha(S_0) = \{S_0, \emptyset\}, \qquad \alpha(\emptyset) = \ast.

Proof. From the decoration, we have S_0 = \{S_0, \emptyset\}. Hence \emptyset \in S_0. The only other element reachable from S_0 by taking elements is \emptyset. The set \{S_0, \emptyset\} is closed under \alpha because \alpha(S_0) = \{S_0,\emptyset\} and \alpha(\emptyset)=\ast (the distinguished point, which corresponds to \emptyset under the isomorphism). Thus it is a subcoalgebra. Any subcoalgebra containing S_0 must contain \emptyset because \emptyset is an element of S_0, so this is the minimal one. ∎

Thus the “observable” part generated by the primordial distinction is trivial: only the two elements S_0 and \emptyset are forced. The full universe U is far larger and contains all finitely branching trees; it is the maximal self‑consistent structure.

4.4 The Forced Universe Lemma

The previous proposition shows that the single equation S = \{S,\emptyset\} does not force the entire universe. What, then, is the minimal structure that does generate all of U? The answer lies not in a single set but in the functor F itself.

Lemma 4.4 (Forced Universe). Let U be the final coalgebra of F. Then U is the smallest set satisfying:

1. \emptyset \in U (interpreted as the leaf tree);
2. If A is a finite subset of U, then the tree whose root has children A belongs to U.

Moreover, every element of U can be obtained by iterating this closure from \emptyset (allowing infinite iterations). In coalgebraic terms, U is the carrier of the final coalgebra and is the terminal object in the category of F-coalgebras; it is the unique fixed point of the functor up to isomorphism.

Proof. The description of U as the set of all finitely branching trees immediately satisfies (1) and (2). Conversely, any set X containing \emptyset and closed under taking finite subsets (as trees) must contain all finite-depth trees; by coinduction it must also contain all infinite trees because they are limits of finite ones in the final coalgebra construction. Hence U is the minimal such set. The uniqueness follows from the terminality of the final coalgebra. ∎

Thus, while the primordial distinction S_0 is a specific fixed point, the full universe is forced not by a single equation but by the closure under the functor—the imperative to include all finite subsets of already existing structures. This can be interpreted as the mathematical content of the original question: the simplest self‑consistent structure that can distinguish itself from nothing is not a set but a functor that generates a universe.

