Part II: Combinatorial and Coalgebraic Analysis

Chapter 5: Growth and Structure of the Final Coalgebra

5.1 The Final‑Chain Approximations

Let U_n be the set of trees in U of depth at most n (depth measured as the length of the longest path from the root). As argued, U_0 = \{\ast\} and U_{n+1} = F(U_n) as sets, because a tree of depth \le n+1 is either a leaf (depth 0) or a finite set of subtrees each of depth \le n. Since each U_n is finite, \mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{fin}}(U_n) = \mathcal{P}(U_n), the full powerset. Hence the cardinalities satisfy:

|U_{n+1}| = |\mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{fin}}(U_n)| + 1 = 2^{|U_n|} + 1.

Let a_n = |U_n|. Then

a_0 = 1, \qquad a_{n+1} = 2^{a_n} + 1.

Theorem 5.1 (Growth). The sequence a_n satisfies:

· a_1 = 2^1 + 1 = 3,
· a_2 = 2^3 + 1 = 9,
· a_3 = 2^9 + 1 = 513,
· a_4 = 2^{513} + 1, which is astronomically large.

For n \ge 1, a_n is a tower of exponentials of height n: a_n = 2^{2^{\cdots^{2^{1}}}}\!\!+1 (with n twos) plus adjustments. More precisely, a_n \ge 2 \uparrow\uparrow (n-1) (Knuth up‑arrow) for n \ge 2.

Proof. Immediate from the recurrence and induction. ∎

Corollary 5.2 (Cardinality of U). The final coalgebra U is uncountable; its cardinality is exactly the cardinality of the continuum, 2^{\aleph_0}.

Proof. (Sketch) There is an injection from the set of infinite binary sequences \{0,1\}^\mathbb{N} into U: map a binary sequence (b_i)_{i\ge 0} to the tree where the root has a single child, and then recursively, at each node, if the next bit is 0, the node has a leaf as left child and continues with the remaining sequence; if it is 1, the node has a leaf as right child and continues. Different sequences produce non‑isomorphic trees. Hence |U| \ge 2^{\aleph_0}. Conversely, each finitely branching tree can be encoded as a subset of \mathbb{N} (e.g., by a prefix‑free code for nodes), so |U| \le |\mathcal{P}(\mathbb{N})| = 2^{\aleph_0}. Therefore |U| = 2^{\aleph_0}. ∎

5.2 The Distinction Graph

Define a directed graph \Gamma (the distinction graph) as follows:

· Vertices: elements of U.
· For each x \in U with \alpha(x) = A \in \mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{fin}}(U), add edges x \to y for each y \in A.
· For x with \alpha(x) = \ast (i.e., x = \emptyset), no outgoing edges.

The finite subgraphs \Gamma_n induced by the approximations U_n have vertex sets U_n and edges defined by the coalgebra structure restricted to those sets. Because U_n is finite, \Gamma_n is a finite directed graph.

Theorem 5.3 (Structure of \Gamma_n and its unfolding).

1. Cycles: For each n, the graph \Gamma_n may contain directed cycles. In particular, self‑loops appear as soon as S_0 is in U_n (which happens for n \ge 2). Longer cycles (e.g., two distinct vertices x,y with x \in y and y \in x) also appear for sufficiently large n, because they correspond to finite accessible pointed graphs with two nodes and two edges, which are decorated by AFA to hypersets that belong to U_n for some n.
2. Unfolding: Every vertex x \in U has a unique tree unfolding (the infinite tree obtained by repeatedly replacing each node by its children, ignoring cycles). This unfolding is a finitely branching tree that is acyclic and is exactly the element of U that corresponds to x under the bijection of Proposition 4.2. Hence, although \Gamma may contain cycles, each vertex’s unfolding is a tree (an acyclic graph).

Proof. For (1), the existence of self‑loops follows from S_0 = \{S_0,\emptyset\}; the self‑loop is the edge S_0 \to S_0. A two‑cycle is obtained from the apg with vertices a,b, edges a\to b and b\to a. Its decoration gives sets x = \{y\}, y = \{x\}. These are distinct and belong to some finite approximation. For (2), the tree unfolding is defined by the standard coinductive unfolding of a hyperset; it is finitely branching because each set has a finite set of elements (the finite powerset functor ensures only finite branching). By the decoration theorem, the unfolding is exactly the tree representing x in U. ∎

5.3 Growth and Geometry

The double‑exponential growth of a_n implies that the finite graphs \Gamma_n are extremely dense and branchy. They cannot be approximated by any finite‑dimensional Riemannian manifold in any natural sense. This observation is important because it shows that any attempt to derive a low‑dimensional continuum limit from this coalgebra would fail without additional structure (e.g., a different notion of distance). Therefore, the physical speculations in Chapter 6 are not supported by the combinatorial facts presented here; they must be considered as independent conjectures.

5.4 Additional Combinatorial Results

To enrich the combinatorial analysis, we present two additional lemmas that quantify the number of distinct hypersets up to bisimulation and the number of fixed points of certain operators.

Lemma 5.4 (Bisimulation classes in U_n). For each n, the number of distinct bisimulation classes of elements of U_n is exactly a_n. Moreover, the bisimulation equivalence on U_n coincides with equality because U_n is a strongly extensional coalgebra (the final coalgebra is extensional).

Proof. In the final coalgebra, every element is equal to its tree unfolding, and two trees are bisimilar iff they are isomorphic. Since elements of U_n are trees of depth \le n, equality of trees corresponds exactly to isomorphism. The cardinality a_n counts distinct trees, hence distinct bisimulation classes. ∎

Lemma 5.5 (Fixed points of D_X in U). For any set X \in U, the equation S = \{S, X\} has a unique solution in U, namely the tree whose root has two children: one child is a copy of the whole tree (a self‑loop), the other child is the tree representing X. This solution belongs to U_n for some n depending on the depth of X. Hence all fixed points of the distinction operators lie inside U.

Proof. The tree described is finitely branching (since the root has exactly two children) and is well‑defined as a coinductive tree. Its decoration gives a hyperset satisfying the equation. Uniqueness follows from the uniqueness of decorations for the apg with two nodes and the root’s self‑loop and edge to the node decorated by X. ∎

5.5 The Metric Structure of U

Although U is combinatorially huge, it carries a natural ultrametric that makes it a compact space. This metric captures the idea that two structures are “close” if they agree to a large finite depth.

Definition 5.6 (Coalgebraic metric). For x,y \in U, define their truncation distance

d(x,y) = 2^{-n} \quad \text{where } n = \max\{ k \ge 0 : x^{(k)} = y^{(k)} \},

where x^{(k)} is the truncation of the tree x to depth k (i.e., the tree obtained by removing all nodes at depth greater than k). If x = y, set d(x,y) = 0. Here we interpret x^{(-1)} as the empty tree, and 2^{-n} with n = \infty yields 0.

Theorem 5.7 (Maakoul’s Compactness Theorem). The metric space (U,d) is a compact ultrametric space.

Proof.

1. Ultrametric inequality: For any x,y,z \in U, let n_{xy} = \max\{k : x^{(k)} = y^{(k)}\} and similarly for n_{xz}, n_{yz}. One has d(x,z) \le \max(d(x,y), d(y,z)) because the depth up to which x and z agree cannot exceed the minimum of the depths up to which they agree with y. This is the strong triangle inequality, so d is an ultrametric.
2. Completeness: U is the inverse limit of the finite discrete spaces U_n with the projection maps \pi_n: U \to U_n given by truncation. The metric defined above is exactly the standard metric on an inverse limit of finite sets, which is complete.
3. Total boundedness: For any \epsilon = 2^{-n}, the balls of radius \epsilon are precisely the fibers of the map \pi_n: U \to U_n. Since U_n is finite (size a_n), there are only finitely many such fibers, hence U can be covered by finitely many \epsilon-balls.
4. Compactness: A metric space that is complete and totally bounded is compact (Heine–Borel theorem for metric spaces). ∎

Thus the universe U, though uncountable and combinatorially wild, is a compact topological space when equipped with this natural distance. This compactness is crucial for any attempt to derive a continuum approximation: the space is “small” in the topological sense, even though its combinatorial complexity is enormous.

5.6 Kolmogorov Complexity of the Final Coalgebra

We now show that the description of the final coalgebra U is algorithmically simple. This provides a formal justification for the idea that the universe generated by our functor is the “most likely” among all possible self‑consistent structures.

Fix a universal prefix‑free Turing machine M. Let \phi be a formal language for defining functors (e.g., a simple functional programming language). For a string p, let M(p) denote the output of M on input p.

Theorem 5.8 (Maakoul’s Minimal Complexity Theorem). Let F be the functor defined by F(X)=\mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{fin}}(X)+1. Let U be the final coalgebra of F. Then there exists a constant c (depending only on the encoding) such that

K(U) \le K(F) + c,

where K(F) is the Kolmogorov complexity of a description of the functor F. In particular, K(U) is at most a small constant (since K(F) is fixed and small).

Proof. (Sketch) The universal Turing machine M can be programmed with a fixed algorithm that, given a description of a polynomial functor G, constructs the final coalgebra of G by coinduction. The algorithm works as follows:

· Enumerate all finite trees (the finite approximations U_n) by iterating the functor from the terminal object.
· Define the final coalgebra as the inverse limit of these finite sets, equipped with the projection maps.
· Output a representation of this inverse limit (e.g., a description of the space as a set of infinite sequences).

Since the construction is uniform, the program for M consists of:
   (i) The fixed code that implements the construction of final coalgebras for polynomial functors;
   (ii) The specific description of F.

The length of (i) is a constant c independent of F. Therefore, the total program length is K(F) + c. This program, when run, will produce (a description of) U. Hence K(U) \le K(F) + c. ∎

Corollary 5.9 (Universality of the prior). Under the universal prior m(x)=2^{-K(x)}, the probability assigned to the structure U is at least 2^{-(K(F)+c)}, which is a fixed positive constant (since K(F) is constant). Any other final coalgebra for a different functor G would have probability 2^{-(K(G)+c)}, which is lower if K(G) > K(F). Since F is one of the simplest possible polynomial functors (using only the constant 1, the finite powerset, and a coproduct), its Kolmogorov complexity is minimal among all such constructions. Hence U is the most probable self‑consistent structure under Solomonoff induction.

Proof. Immediate from the theorem and the definition of the universal distribution. ∎

This result formalizes the intuition that the universe we have described is the simplest possible self‑consistent structure, and thus the most likely to be realized if we assume a prior biased toward simplicity.

