Appendix A: Explicit Construction of the Final Coalgebra

In this appendix we provide a rigorous proof that the set of all finitely branching trees carries a final coalgebra structure for the functor F(X)=\mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{fin}}(X)+1. We also detail the correspondence with hypersets under AFA.

A.1 Trees and Truncations

Let \mathbb{N}^* denote the set of finite sequences of natural numbers (the addresses of nodes in a tree). A finitely branching tree is a non‑empty set T \subseteq \mathbb{N}^* closed under prefixes and such that for every node u \in T, the set of children \{ n \in \mathbb{N} : u n \in T \} is finite. The root is the empty sequence \varepsilon. A leaf is a node with no children. We label leaves by a distinguished symbol \ast; equivalently we may think that leaves are exactly those nodes with no children, and the label \ast is implicit. However, to match the functor +1 we need an explicit “empty” element. Therefore we define U as the set of all such trees, with the convention that a tree consisting of a single node (the root) is considered a leaf and corresponds to the element \ast in the +1 part.

Define \alpha: U \to F(U) by

\alpha(t) = 
\begin{cases}
\ast & \text{if } t \text{ is a leaf},\\
\{ t_u : u \text{ is a child of the root of } t \} & \text{otherwise},
\end{cases}

where t_u denotes the subtree of t rooted at the child u.

Lemma A.1. The map \alpha is well defined and F-coalgebra structure on U.

Proof. If t is a leaf, \alpha(t)=\ast \in 1 \subseteq F(U). If t is not a leaf, the set of its immediate subtrees is finite because the root has finitely many children; each subtree is again a finitely branching tree, hence an element of U. Thus \alpha(t) \in \mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{fin}}(U) \subseteq F(U). ∎

A.2 Finality of (U,\alpha)

Let (X,\beta) be an arbitrary F-coalgebra. Define a map h: X \to U by coinduction: for each x \in X, we construct a tree h(x) as follows. If \beta(x) = \ast, then h(x) is the leaf. Otherwise \beta(x) = \{x_1,\dots,x_k\} is a finite set; then h(x) is the tree whose root has children h(x_1),\dots,h(x_k). This definition is justified by the following standard coinductive principle: the map h is the unique homomorphism from (X,\beta) to the final coalgebra, and it can be seen as the limit of the finite truncations.

More formally, define h_n: X \to U_n by induction on n:

· h_0(x) = \ast for all x (the unique element of U_0).
· Given h_n, define h_{n+1}(x) as: if \beta(x) = \ast then h_{n+1}(x) = \ast; otherwise \beta(x) = \{x_1,\dots,x_k\} and set h_{n+1}(x) to be the tree whose root has children h_n(x_1),\dots,h_n(x_k) (all of which are in U_n, so the resulting tree is in U_{n+1}).

Because the maps \pi_{n+1,n}: U_{n+1} \to U_n (truncation) satisfy \pi_{n+1,n}(h_{n+1}(x)) = h_n(x), the family \{h_n\} defines a cone over the inverse system, and thus a unique map h: X \to \lim_{\leftarrow} U_n = U (the inverse limit is exactly the set of infinite trees). One verifies that h is a coalgebra homomorphism, i.e., \alpha \circ h = F(h) \circ \beta. Uniqueness follows from the universal property of the limit.

Theorem A.2. (U,\alpha) is a final F-coalgebra.

Proof. The construction above provides a morphism from any coalgebra to U. The inverse limit argument shows that this morphism is unique. ∎

A.3 Correspondence with Hypersets

Given a finitely branching tree t \in U, consider the accessible pointed graph (G_t,\to,r_t) where G_t is the set of nodes of t, u \to v iff v is a child of u, and r_t is the root. By AFA, this apg has a unique decoration d_t. The decorated set at the root is a hyperset that we denote by \mathsf{set}(t).

Conversely, given a hyperset s (i.e., any set in ZFC+AFA), its transitive closure can be unfolded into an apg; the tree obtained by repeatedly replacing each node by its children (ignoring cycles) yields a finitely branching tree (the canonical unfolding). This tree is unique and we denote it by \mathsf{tree}(s).

Proposition A.3. The maps \mathsf{set}: U \to V (where V is the universe of sets) and \mathsf{tree}: V \to U are inverses of each other. Moreover, for any t \in U, \alpha(t) = \mathsf{tree}^{-1}(\{\mathsf{set}(t_u) : u \text{ child of root}\}) in the sense of the coalgebra structure, and this is consistent with the membership relation.

Proof. (Sketch) The decoration theorem ensures that every tree gives a set, and the unfolding of a set gives a tree. Because AFA guarantees that two sets are equal iff their apgs are bisimilar, and the tree unfolding is the canonical bisimilar representative, the correspondence is bijective. The coalgebra structure corresponds to the membership relation: the children of the root are exactly the elements of the set. ∎

