Appendix B: Cardinality and Growth – Detailed Proofs

B.1 Recurrence for |U_n|

Let U_n be the set of trees of depth at most n. A tree of depth \le n+1 is either a leaf (depth 0) or a tree whose root has a finite set of children, each of which is a subtree of depth \le n. Because U_n is finite, the set of possible finite subsets of U_n is exactly its powerset. Therefore:

U_{n+1} = \{\ast\} \cup \{ \text{tree with children } A : A \subseteq U_n \text{ finite} \}.

Since every subset of a finite set is finite, we have a bijection between U_{n+1} \setminus \{\ast\} and \mathcal{P}(U_n). Hence

|U_{n+1}| = |\mathcal{P}(U_n)| + 1 = 2^{|U_n|} + 1.

With a_n = |U_n| and a_0 = 1, this yields the recurrence a_{n+1} = 2^{a_n} + 1.

B.2 Tower‑Exponential Bound

Define the iterated exponential notation 2 \uparrow\uparrow k (Knuth up‑arrow) by 2 \uparrow\uparrow 1 = 2, 2 \uparrow\uparrow (k+1) = 2^{2 \uparrow\uparrow k}.

Lemma B.1. For n \ge 1, a_n \ge 2 \uparrow\uparrow n.

Proof. By induction. For n=1, a_1 = 3 \ge 2 = 2 \uparrow\uparrow 1. Assume a_n \ge 2 \uparrow\uparrow n. Then

a_{n+1} = 2^{a_n} + 1 \ge 2^{2 \uparrow\uparrow n} = 2 \uparrow\uparrow (n+1).

∎

B.3 Cardinality of U

We prove |U| = 2^{\aleph_0} under the continuum hypothesis or in ZFC (since 2^{\aleph_0} is the cardinality of the continuum).

Lower bound. Define an injection f: \{0,1\}^\mathbb{N} \to U as follows. For a binary sequence (b_i)_{i\ge 0}, construct a tree where the root has a single child, and then recursively, if b_0 = 0, that child is a leaf; if b_0 = 1, that child is a leaf; actually we need a more careful encoding to ensure distinct trees. A simpler injection: map (b_i) to the tree where the root has a left child that is a leaf and a right child that is the tree obtained from the tail of the sequence. More formally, define T(b_0,b_1,\dots) as: if the sequence is empty, the tree is a leaf; otherwise, the root has two children: left child is a leaf, right child is T(b_1,b_2,\dots) if b_0=0, else right child is a leaf and left child is T(b_1,b_2,\dots)? This gives a binary tree encoding. There are standard encodings of infinite binary sequences into infinite binary trees (e.g., the tree of prefixes). Because U contains all such trees, |U| \ge 2^{\aleph_0}.

Upper bound. Each finitely branching tree can be encoded as a subset of \mathbb{N} by listing the nodes in a fixed enumeration and marking which nodes are present. Since the set of all subsets of \mathbb{N} has cardinality 2^{\aleph_0}, we have |U| \le 2^{\aleph_0}. Thus |U| = 2^{\aleph_0}.

