Appendix C: Metric Structure and Compactness

We provide full proofs for the properties of the ultrametric d on U.

C.1 Definition and Ultrametric Property

For x,y \in U, let

n(x,y) = \max\{ k \ge 0 : x^{(k)} = y^{(k)} \},

where x^{(k)} is the truncation of the tree x to depth k (i.e., the tree obtained by deleting all nodes at depth >k). If x = y, we set n(x,y) = \infty and d(x,y)=0. Otherwise, define d(x,y) = 2^{-n(x,y)}.

Lemma C.1. d is an ultrametric: for all x,y,z \in U,

1. d(x,y) = 0 \iff x = y.
2. d(x,y) = d(y,x).
3. d(x,z) \le \max\{ d(x,y), d(y,z) \}.

Proof. (1) and (2) are immediate. For (3), let m = \min\{ n(x,y), n(y,z) \}. Then x^{(m)} = y^{(m)} and y^{(m)} = z^{(m)}, so x^{(m)} = z^{(m)}. Hence n(x,z) \ge m. Thus

d(x,z) = 2^{-n(x,z)} \le 2^{-m} = \max(2^{-n(x,y)}, 2^{-n(y,z)}) = \max(d(x,y), d(y,z)).

∎

C.2 Completeness

Consider the inverse limit construction U = \lim_{\leftarrow} U_n with projections \pi_n: U \to U_n (truncation). The metric d is compatible with the product topology on the limit: a sequence (x_m) converges to x iff for each n, eventually \pi_n(x_m) = \pi_n(x). The limit of a Cauchy sequence in this metric converges to a unique tree, because the projections define a Cauchy sequence in each finite discrete space U_n, which stabilizes after finitely many steps. Hence U is complete.

C.3 Total Boundedness

For any \epsilon > 0, choose n such that 2^{-n} < \epsilon. The balls of radius \epsilon are unions of the equivalence classes of the relation “x^{(n)} = y^{(n)}”. Since U_n is finite (size a_n), there are only finitely many such classes. Thus U can be covered by finitely many \epsilon-balls; i.e., U is totally bounded.

C.4 Compactness

A metric space is compact iff it is complete and totally bounded (Heine‑Borel theorem for metric spaces). Therefore (U,d) is compact.

