Appendix D: Kolmogorov Complexity Upper Bound

We fix a universal prefix‑free Turing machine M and a standard encoding of finite objects as binary strings.

D.1 Encoding the Functor

The functor F is defined by the expression \mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{fin}}(X)+1. We can encode this description as a finite binary string p_F of length, say, c_0 bits (a constant). For definiteness, we may use a simple functional language: “functor F(X) = (finite_powerset X) + 1”. The exact constant is irrelevant; what matters is that it is fixed and independent of the coalgebra.

D.2 Universal Construction of Final Coalgebras

We claim there exists a fixed program (of length c_1) that, given a description of a polynomial functor G, outputs a description of the final coalgebra of G. This program works as follows:

1. From the description of G, construct the sequence G^n(1) (where 1 is a terminal object) up to \omega steps, then take the inverse limit. For polynomial functors, this limit can be described as the set of all infinite sequences (x_0,x_1,\dots) with x_n \in G^n(1) and the consistency conditions.
2. Encode the resulting limit as a set of infinite trees (or as a subspace of a product space) in a standard way.

Because the construction is uniform, the program is fixed. Its length c_1 does not depend on G. Therefore, to obtain a description of U, we concatenate p_F with this program, or equivalently, we have a program that first reads p_F and then runs the universal construction.

Thus there exists a program p of length |p_F| + c_1 that outputs a description of U. Hence

K(U) \le |p| \le K(F) + c,

where K(F) is the Kolmogorov complexity of the description of F (at most the length of p_F), and c = c_1 is a constant. Since K(F) is itself a fixed small constant (the description of F is short), we have K(U) = O(1).

D.3 Remarks on Lower Bounds

Lower bounds are much harder; one would need to show that no significantly shorter description can produce the same structure. However, the final coalgebra is highly symmetric and contains all finitely branching trees, so it is plausible that its complexity is exactly the complexity of the description of F. This remains an open problem.

