Appendix E: Non‑Well‑Founded Set Theory (AFA)

This appendix reviews the necessary background on Aczel’s Anti‑Foundation Axiom and its consequences.

E.1 Accessible Pointed Graphs

Recall Definition 2.1: an apg is a directed graph with a distinguished root such that every node is reachable from the root by a finite path. The edge relation is often denoted by \to.

E.2 Decorations and the Solution Lemma

A decoration is a function assigning a set to each node such that each node’s set is exactly the set of decorations of its children. The key result is:

Theorem E.1 (AFA). Every accessible pointed graph has a unique decoration.

This theorem implies that any system of set equations that can be represented as an apg has a unique solution. In particular, the equation x = \{x\} (Quine atom) has a unique solution, denoted \Omega.

E.3 Bisimulation

Two apgs (G,\to,r) and (G',\to',r') are bisimilar if there exists a relation R \subseteq G \times G' such that:

· (r,r') \in R;
· whenever (x,y) \in R and x \to z, there exists w with y \to' w and (z,w) \in R;
· whenever (x,y) \in R and y \to' w, there exists z with x \to z and (z,w) \in R.

Theorem E.2 (Aczel). Two decorations of two apgs are equal iff the apgs are bisimilar.

Thus the uniqueness of decorations is closely tied to bisimulation.

E.4 Final Coalgebra Interpretation

The class of all sets under AFA can be seen as the final coalgebra of the powerset functor \mathcal{P}. However, the presence of AFA forces the existence of all finitely branching trees; indeed, the universe of hypersets is exactly the final coalgebra of the finite powerset functor (when one restricts to hereditarily finite sets) or the full powerset functor (for all sets). Our functor \mathcal{P}_{\mathrm{fin}}+1 gives the “small” universe of all sets whose transitive closure is countable? Actually, it gives precisely the sets that are obtained by starting from \emptyset and repeatedly taking finite subsets (allowing infinite iteration). This includes all hypersets whose membership graphs are finitely branching (i.e., every node has finite out‑degree). This is a natural restriction that avoids the full impredicativity of the powerset.

E.5 Examples

· The Quine atom \Omega satisfies \Omega = \{\Omega\}. Its apg is a single node with a self‑loop. It is not in our U because its tree unfolding would require an infinite chain of self‑reference? Actually, \Omega corresponds to an infinite tree where the root has one child which is itself; this is a finitely branching tree (each node has exactly one child), so \Omega \in U. So our U contains all hypersets whose membership graphs are finitely branching. This includes many non‑well‑founded sets.

